]]. For example, some languages, including [[Chinese language|Chinese]] and [[Arabic]], cover several [[Mutual intelligibility|mutually unintelligible]] [[Variety (linguistics)|varieties]] and are sometimes considered single languages and sometimes language families. Conversely, [[colloquial]] [[Register_(sociolinguistics)#Register_as_formality_scale|registers]] of [[Hindi]]  and [[Urdu]] are almost completely mutually intelligible, so they are sometimes classified as one language, [[Hindustani language|Hindustani]], instead of two separate languages.<ref>For further examples of mutually intelligible varieties that are often, and even legally, classified as separate languages, see [[Malay language]], [[Persian language]] and [[Serbo-Croatian]].</ref>\n*Second, there is no single criterion for how much knowledge is sufficient to be counted as a [[Second language|second-language]] speaker. For example, English has about 400&nbsp;million native speakers but, depending on the criterion chosen, can be said to have as many as 2&nbsp;billion speakers.<ref>{{Cite journal|url = http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayAbstract?fromPage=online&aid=1742576&fileId=S0266078408000023|title = Two thousand million?|last = Crystal|first = David|date = March 2008|journal = English Today|doi = 10.1017/S0266078408000023|pmid = |accessdate = }}</ref>\n\n==''Ethnologue'' (2020, 23rd edition)==\nThe following 34 languages are listed as having 45 million or more total speakers in the 2019 edition of [[SIL Ethnologue|''Ethnologue'']], a language reference published by [[SIL International]], which is based in the [[United States]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ethnologue.com/statistics/size|title=Summary by language size|website=Ethnologue|accessdate=2019-03-01}}</ref> Entries identified by ''Ethnologue'' as macrolanguages are not included in this section.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! rowspan=2 data-sort-type=\"number\" | Rank\n! rowspan=2|Language\n! rowspan=2|[[Language family|Family]]\n! rowspan=2|Branch\n! colspan=2| [[First language]] (L1)\n! colspan=2| [[Second language]] (L2)\n! rowspan=2 data-sort-type=\"number\" | Total<br>No. of<br>speakers\n|-\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | No. of<br> speakers\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | Rank\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | No. of<br>speakers\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | Rank\n|-\n| 1\n| [[English language|English]]\n| [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]]\n| [[Germanic languages|Germanic]]\n| 369.7 million\n| 3\n| data-sort-value=\"898.4 million\" ! | 898.4 million\n| 1\n| data-sort-value=\"1268.1 million\" ! | 1.268 billion<ref>{{e22|eng|English}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2\n| [[Mandarin Chinese]]  (incl. [[Standard Chinese]])\n| [[Sino-Tibetan languages|Sino-Tibetan]]\n| [[Sinitic languages|Sinitic]]\n| 921.5 million\n| 1\n| data-sort-value=\"198.7 million\" ! | 198.7 million\n| 4\n| data-sort-value=\"1120.2 million\" ! | 1.120 billion<ref>{{e22|cmn|Chinese, Mandarin}}</ref>\n|-\n| 3\n| [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]]\n| [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan]]\n| 342.0 million\n| 4\n| data-sort-value=\"274.2 million\" ! | 295.3 million\n| 2\n| data-sort-value=\"637 million\" ! | 637.3 million<ref>{{e22|hin|Hindi}}</ref>\n|-\n| 4\n| [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n| [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]]\n| [[Romance languages|Romance]]\n| 463.0 million\n| 2\n| data-sort-value=\"74.2 million\" ! | 74.9 million\n| 9\n| data-sort-value=\"534.3 million\" ! | 537.9 million<ref>{{e22|spa|Spanish}}</ref>\n|-\n| 5\n| [[French language|French]]\n| [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]]\n| [[Romance languages|Romance]]\n| 77.3 million\n| 15\n| data-sort-value=\"202.6 million\" ! | 199.3 million\n| 3\n| data-sort-value=\"279.8 million\" ! | 276.6 million<ref>{{e22|fra|French}}</ref>\n|-\n| 6\n| [[Modern Standard Arabic|Standard Arabic]]\n| [[Afro-Asiatic languages|Afro-Asiatic]]\n| [[Semitic languages|Semitic]]\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| data-sort-value=\"273.9 million\" ! 